results.occurrenceRemarks: Baobab trees growing on a reef of metamorphic rock on the "Island of the Manatees", where the Eco-Lodge de Brousse is located. Trees are mature, laden with dry fruit (hairy and green, with a hard shell containing hard black/brown c-shaped seeds in a matrix of dry white pulp that is slightly sweet with the texture of popped popcorn, and a network of dry red vascular tissue). The white pulp is relished by Green Savanna Monkeys (Chlorocebus tantalus).

results.occurrenceRemarks: This is a famous historic tree growing wild in the Pans. The explorer Livingstone carved his initials in the tree, and described it in his writings as one of the few reliable landmarks in an almost treeless part of the Kalihari Desert. This baobab is about twenty meters high, and is likely three centuries old. This is truly a remote part of the Kalihari, with no paved roads or paved runways within about 100 km.
